hatma Gandhi told them that if they could bring about m=\r\narriages between Harijan girls and higher caste gentlemen, such marriages w=\r\nould have his blessings; and that he (visitor) would like to have Bhagavan=\r\n=E2=80=99s views in the matter. &lt;br&gt;\n&gt; &lt;br&gt;\n&gt; Bhagavan said, =E2=80=\r\n=9CIf Mahatma Gandhi has said so, we will all hear what he has said. What m=\r\nore is there for us to do? He is a distinguished man and is working in that=\r\n field.What have we to do with that?=E2=80=9D &lt;br&gt;\n&gt; &lt;br&gt;\n&gt; Turning t=\r\no us, Bhagavan added,=E2=80=9CIf I open my mouth, something will appear in =\r\nthe papers that so-and-so has also said such-and-such a thing. The next day=\r\n there will be people to criticise it. Our business is to keep quiet. If we=\r\n enter into all these, people will naturally ask, and justifiably, =E2=80=\r\n=98Why is he interfering in all these instead of keeping quiet?=E2=80=99 &lt;b=\r\nr&gt;\n&gt; &lt;br&gt;\n&gt; Similarly if Mahatma Gandhi keeps quiet leaving aside all=\r\n his activities,they will ask, =E2=80=98Why is he keeping quiet instead of =\r\nengaging in all these activities?=E2=80=99 He must do what he has come for.=\r\n We must do what we have come for.=E2=80=9D&lt;br&gt;\n&gt; &lt;br&gt;\n&gt; Source: DAY =\r\nBY DAY WITH BHAGAVAN From the Diary of A. DEVARAJA MUDALIAR &lt;br&gt;\n&gt; &lt;br&gt;\n=\r\n&gt; -- &lt;br&gt;\n&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;/p&gt;\n\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n     \n\n\n\n \n\n\n\n\n\n&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;/div=\r\n&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;br&gt;\n\n      \r\n--0-1866023794-1270188991=:66128--\r\n\n"}}